text: Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2014) 98:45–60 DOI 10.1007/s00253-013-5373-0 Intriguing properties of the angucycline antibiotic auricin and complex regulation of its biosynthesis Jan Kormanec & Renata Novakova & Erik Mingyar & Lubomira Feckova Received: 8 October 2013 / Revised: 29 October 2013 / Accepted: 30 October 2013 / Published online: 22 November 2013 # Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg 2013 Abstract Streptomyces bacteria are major producers of bio- active natural products, including many antibiotics. We iden- tified a gene cluster, aur1 , in a large linear plasmid of Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM3239. The cluster is respon- sible for the production of a new angucycline polyketide antibiotic auricin. Several tailoring biosynthetic genes were scatted in rather distant aur1 flanking regions. Auricin was produced in a very narrow growth phase interval of several hours after entry into stationary phase, after which it was degraded to non-active metabolites because of its instability at the high pH values reached after the production stage. Strict transcriptional regulation of the auricin biosynthetic gene cluster has been demonstrated, including feed-forward and feedback control by auricin intermediates via several of the huge number of regulatory genes present in the aur1 cluster. The complex mechanism may ensure strict confinement of auricin production to a specific growth stage. Keywords Antibiotics . Angucycline . Auricin . Polyketide . Regulation . Secondary metabolite . Streptomyces

Actinomycetes, mainly the genus Streptomyces , are rich sources of secondary metabolites with various biological ac- tivities including antimicrobial, antifungal, antihelmintic, an- titumor, antiviral, immunosuppresive, and enzyme inhibitory effects (Hopwood 2007). In general, one or only several secondary metabolites were identified in a particular strain. However, the evaluation of several actinomycetes genomes J. Kormanec (*) : R. Novakova : E. Mingyar : L. Feckova Institute of Molecular Biology, Slovak Academy of Sciences, Dubravska cesta 21, 845 51 Bratislava, Slovak Republic e-mail: jan.kormanec@savba.sk revealed much higher secondary metabolic potential than expected from the analysis of culture fluids; for instance, Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) is known to produce four antibiotics, yet its genome contains at least 18 additional gene clusters putatively involved in secondary metabolite produc- tion (Bentley et al. 2002). Similar results were found in other Streptomyces genomes (Ikeda et al. 2003; Ohnishi et al. 2008). These so-called cryptic gene clusters are likely silent, tightly regulated, or expressed under specific conditions (Gross 2007). Understanding the mechanisms underlying the silencing of these cryptic gene clusters may lead to the pro- duction of new antimicrobials and other useful bioactive compounds.

We previously identified and characterized one of such cryptic clusters, aur1 , in our model strain, Streptomyces aureofaciens CCM3239. The aur1 cluster is similar to several type II polyketide synthase (PKS) gene clusters for angucycline antibiotics, such as landomycin, jadomycin, and urdamycin (Novakova et al. 2002). Indeed, we confirmed that the aur1 cluster is responsible for an antibiotic compound that was named auricin. However, auricin was produced in very low levels that hampered its purification and structural eluci- dation for many years. Interestingly, also some other homol- ogous angucycline clusters, like alp for kinamycin from Streptomyces ambofaciens (Pang et al. 2004; Bunet et al. 2011), pga for gaudimycin from Streptomyces sp. PGA64 (Metsä-Ketelä et al. 2004; Palmu et al. 2007), cab for un- known angucycline from Streptomyces sp. HO21 (Palmu et al. 2007), and ovm for oviedomycin from Streptomyces antibioitcus (Lombó et al. 2004), have similarly limited ex- pression. This indicated that these clusters might be strictly regulated or induced by specific conditions. Recently, we found that auricin was produced in a very narrow growth phase interval just after entry into stationary phase. Moreover, auricin was very unstable and quickly degraded at standard growth conditions, accounting for our previous failure. The pH has been found to be a critical parameter of auricin stability (Kutas et al. 2013).

We supposed that the pattern of auricin accumulation arises from a strict and complex regulation. Many genes encoding transcriptional regulators of different families have been lo- cated near or within the auricin cluster, and several of them have already been found to have a role in auricin regulation (Novakova et al. 2005, 2010a, 2011b, 2013; Rehakova et al. 2013). Although several excellent reviews on the regulatory aspects of antibiotic biosynthesis have already been published (Bibb 2005; Liu et al. 2013; Martin and Liras 2010; van Wezel and McDowall 2011), the results of our studies indicate a rather complex and unusual regulation of auricin biosynthesis, including not only a classical hierarchical structure present in many antibiotic clusters but also some horizontal interactions among auricin pathway-specific regulators. This review is a current account of auricin, including its biosynthesis, specific properties, potential exploitation, and complex regulation in comparison to other similar angucycline clusters.

In our model organism, S. aureofaciens CCM3239, we initially cloned an incomplete gene cluster aur1 (containing the aur1A- aur1N region, Fig. 1) for an aromatic type II polyketide (Novakova et al. 2002). Almost all deduced gene products showed high sequence similarities to the corresponding proteins encoded by respective genes from clusters for known angucyclines, such as the lan , urd , and jad clusters for landomycin from Streptomyces cyanogenus; urdamycin from Streptomyces fradiae ; and jadomycin from Streptomyces venezuelae, respectively. The disruption of two essential bio- synthetic genes, aur1D and aur1E, abolished production of an antibiotic compound, which was named auricin (Novakova et al. 2002). Aromatic polyketides comprise a large group of structurally diverse secondary metabolitesproduced by type II PKSs, which catalyze repeated decarboxylative condensation between acyl thioesters. They exhibit various biological activi- ties, such as antibacterial, antitumor, antifungal, antiparasitic, and immunosuppresive effects (Hertweck et al. 2007). Aromatic PKSs comprise three essential subunits referred as minimal PKS: β-ketoacyl synthase α (KSα) which catalyzes the con- densation reaction, β-ketoacyl synthase β (KSβ) or chain length factor involved in determination of polyketide chain length, and acyl carrier protein (ACP) which acts as an anchor for the growing polyketide chain during condensation and subsequent modification reactions. Other PKS subunits, like ketoreductases (KR), aromatase (ARO), and cyclases (CYC), are involved in modification of the nascent polyketide chain to generate specific cyclic polyketides. Various tailoring reactions catalyzed by diverse oxygenases, reductases, methylases, and glycosyltranferases give rise to a final bioactive product

(Hertweck et al. 2007). Although a large repertoire of aromatic polyketides was identified, they all belong to just a few common structural types that include benzoisochromanequinones, tetra- cyclines, angucyclines, anthracyclines, tetracenomycines, and aureolic acids. Angucyclines represent a dominant group of natural aromatic polyketides with broad range of biological activities including antibiotic, antitumor, antiviral, antifungal, platelet aggregation, and enzyme inhibitory effects. They are characterized by the angular shape of the aromatic tetracyclic ring (Fig. 2) (Rohr and Thiericke 1992).

Comparison of the known angucycline clusters (lan for landomycin, urd for urdamycin, jad for jadomycin, ovm for oviedomycin, pga for gaudimycin, sim for simocyclinone, alp for kinamycin, gil for gilvocarcin, saq for saquayamycin, sch for Sch 47554 and Sch 47555) revealed that they all have an identical core organization in the order CYC, KSα, KSβ, ACP, KR, ARO, which is also conserved in the aur1 cluster in the order aur1C , aur1D , aur1E , aur1F, aur1G , aur1H (Fig. 1). The respective six gene products are essential PKS biosynthetic proteins, responsible for the formation of the first stable angucycline intermediate UWM6 (Fig. 2) or its ana- logue 2,3-dehydro-UWM6 (prejadomycin). The CYC, encoded by the aur1C gene, belongs to the category of specific angucycline CYCs that are responsible for the cycli- zation of the last angular aromatic ring (Kulowski et al. 1999; Metsä-Ketelä et al. 2003; Kharel et al. 2012). The PKS- tailoring gene products of the angucycline gene clusters, which are responsible for the first tailoring reactions of the UWM6 intermediate, are similar to proteins of two well- characterized enzyme families: FAD-dependent oxygenases and short chain alcohol dehydrogenase/reductases (SDRs) (Kharel et al. 2012). The aur1 cluster contains two such genes, aur1A and aur1I, encoding proteins with high similar- ities to the tailoring oxygenases involved in the introduction of hydroxyl groups into angucyclines. Aur1A is highly similar to several FAD-dependent oxygenases, such as PgaE (80/87 %), UrdE (73/80 %), and LanE (72/81 %) in the gaudimycin (Metsä-Ketelä et al. 2004; Palmu et al. 2007), urdamycin (Decker and Haag

The aur1J and aur1K genes encode a putative auricin resistance protein and a protein with a similarity to ACP, respectively. They are followed by three genes, aur1L , aur1M, and aur1N, likely involved in a priming of polyketide biosynthesis (Fig. 1). The aur1L gene encodes a protein similar to phosphopantetheinyl transferases which catalyze the activation of ACP by covalent attachment of a CoA- derived phosphopantetheinyl group. The aur1M gene en- codes a protein similar to malonyl-CoA:ACP transacylases that are essential for the first steps of forming polyketide molecules by charging ACP with an extender malonyl unit, and the aur1N gene codes for a protein with similarity to several acyl-CoA carboxylases that are involved in production of the malonyl-CoA precursor (Novakova et al. 2002). The pga cluster for the gaudimycin (Metsä-Ketelä et al. 2004) contains all these three genes in the same order. Other angucycline gene clusters also contain genes for one or two of these proteins, as in the case of oviedomycin (Lombó et al. 2004), jadomycin (Wang et al. 2001), and landomycin (Westrich et al. 1999). The genes encoding these priming PKS enzymes are in general not found in many PKS clusters, and it is thought that these reactions are performed by proteins borrowed from fatty acid biosynthesis (Hertweck et al. 2007). The aur1A–aur1N region represents the core auricin bio- synthetic genes. Afterwards, a region downstream of the aur1

cluster was cloned, revealing 28 new genes encoding proteins involved in deoxysugar biosynthesis and other putative polyketide-related biosynthetic functions (Fig. 1, Table 1). The last four genes, sa17, sa18, sa19, gdh, are likely not involved in auricin biosynthesis, as they encode proteins with similarity to transposase and primary metabolism glutamate dehydrogenase (Table 1) and indicate a likely boundary of the auricin cluster (Novakova et al. 2010b). However, this part is interrupted by a cluster of eight genes, sa1-bpsA, which likely have no proposed function in polyketide biosynthesis, and one of them, bpsA, has been shown to be involved in biosynthesis of the blue pigment indigoidine (Novakova et al. 2010b). Downstream of aur1N , there are four genes (aur1TQSV ) encoding proteins with high similarity to enzymes involved in the initial steps in deoxysugar biosynthesis (Table 1) (Salas and Méndez 2005). Mutational experiments confirmed in- volvement of the aur1TQSV genes in the biosynthesis of the dimethylamino deoxyhexose D-forosamine, a component of auricin (see later; J. Kormanec, unpublished results). However, no gene encoding a glycosyltransferase and amino- transferase was found in this region. Interestingly, these miss- ing deoxysugar genes have been identified in a rather distant upstream region (Fig. 1) (Novakova et al. 2013). The sa59 gene encodes a protein with high similarity to NDP-hexose aminotransferase, which may add an amino group to the deoxyhexose precursor, likely produced by the product of the aur1TQSV genes. The sa52 gene encodes a protein with high similarity to NDP-aminohexose N-dimethyltransferase, which may be responsible for the methylation of this amino group, thus resulting in the final product, D-forosamine. ethyltransferase, which may be responsible for the methylation of this amino group, thus resulting in the final product, D-forosamine. Seven enzymes, Gtt, Gdh, SpnO, SpnN, SpnQ, SpnR, and SpnS, essential for D-forosamine biosynthesis have been characterized in the spinosyn pathway of Saccharopolyspora spinosa (Hong et al. 2008). The auricin cluster and the flanking regions contain all genes encoding proteins homolo- gous to these enzymes (Sa50, Aur1T, Aur1S, Aur1V, Aur1Q, Sa59, and Sa52) (Fig. 1, Table 1). Interestingly, in this distant region, there are two genes, sa46 and sa53, which encode homologues of glycosyltransferase that are involved in the attachment of deoxysugars to polyketide aglycons. They may be candidates for this function to attach D-forosamine to the auricin aglycon. Mutational analysis to confirm role of these genes in biosynthesis of D-forosamine is in progress in our laboratory. In contrast to other antibiotic gene clusters, which are in general closely clustered, the auricin genes are partially scattered across a rather large region containing also genes with no proposed function in auricin synthesis or regulation (Fig. 1, Table 1). The sa59 gene encoding aminotransferase likely involved in D-forosamine biosynthesis is located 48 kb from the core auricin biosynthetic genes. This gene likely represents the other boundary of the auricin cluster, since another PKS cluster is located in the upstream region that has no role in auricin biosynthesis (Novakova et al. 2013).

We identified several promoters which direct expression of the auricin genes (Fig. 1). The transcription of the biosynthetic genes in the central part of the auricin cluster, aur1A–aur1U , which are oriented in the same direction, is directed by the biosynthetic aur1Ap promoter, which is induced after entry into stationary phase and at the time of aerial mycelium formation. Since the aur1Ap promoter directs transcription of a large transcript of about 20,000 nucleotides, which covers the region containing aur1A–aur1U (Fig. 1), it is supposed that it controls all these genes (Novakova et al. 2002, 2005, 2011b). The promoters aur1Pp , aur1Rp , aur1PR2p , aur1Pr3p, and aur1PR4p (Fig. 1, Table 1) govern transcrip- tion of the regulatory genes (Novakova et al. 2005, 2010a, 2011b, 2013; Rehakova et al. 2013). The promoter sa13p directs expression of proposed auricin-tailoring biosynthetic genes ( Rehakova et al. 2013). Auricin production and properties

Most secondary metabolites, including antibiotics, are pro- duced after entry into stationary phase during growth in liquid production media and accumulate to large amounts after prolonged cultivation. We initially found that auricin, which was active against various Gram-positive bacteria, was pro- duced in very low amounts in the late stationary phase (Novakova et al. 2002, 2005). However, later detailed analysis revealed that auricin was produced in a very narrow time interval of several hours after entry into stationary phase. Then, its production dramatically decreased, with only traces being detectable in the late stationary phase (Fig. 3b–d) (Kutas et al. 2013). This unusual feature was related to a transcrip- tional regulation of auricin biosynthesis, since the activity of the auricin biosynthetic promoter aur1Ap similarly decreased in the late stationary phase (Kutas et al. 2013). However, already synthesized auricin very quickly disappeared from the production medium. The loss of yellow and antibiotically active auricin was accompanied by the disappearance of the corresponding auricin peak in HPLC analysis. No clear sig- nificantly stable degradation product could be detected in the culture filtrate, but only a fraction of small unstable peaks with higher mobility (and therefore hydrophilicity) was observed (Fig. 3b), even though purified auricin was stable for days in several organic solvents. Further analysis of the parameters affecting auricin stability revealed that pH was critical. Auricin was stable at acid pH and unstable at neutral or alkaline pH. This quick auricin disappearance in the cultiva- tion medium could be a result of the fluctuation of pH during growth of S. aureofaciens CCM3239, where pH gradually decreased from the neutral pH at the time of inoculation to the most acid level at the time of auricin production, after which pH gradually increased to alkaline values (Fig. 3a). Auricin had no effect on this pH fluctuation (Kutas et al. 2013).

The proposed molecular formula of auricin was assigned to C29H35N1O9 by high-resolution electrospray ionisation mass spectrometry (m /z =542.2039 [M+H]+) (Kutas et al. 2013). However, the MS/MS fragmentation analysis of this ion al- ways revealed only a dominant signal of m/z =142.1239 [M+ H]+, which corresponded to D-forosamine (Kutas et al. 2013). Although structural studies of auricin are still under investi- gation, these mass spectra studies confirmed that angucycline polyketide ring is conjugated with D-forosamine. This indi- cates that auricin is a unique angucycline. D-forosamine was not found in any angucycline yet. It was found in the macrolides spinosyns, spiramycin, and dunaimycin, as well as in the naphtoquinone antibiotic forosamilylgriseucin A (referred in Hong et al. 2008). As described above, all the genes encoding proteins essential for D-forosamine biosyn- thesis (Hong et al. 2008) are present in the auricin cluster or in the flanking regions (Fig. 1, Table 1). Regulation of auricin biosynthesis

The genes encoding enzymes for secondary metabolites are usually clustered and are regulated by pathway-specific tran- scriptional regulators that are located in these clusters. However, due to their partial influence also on other gene clusters, this term has been changed to the so-called cluster- situated regulators (CSR) (Liu et al. 2013). The expression of the CSR genes is controlled by so-called global regulators through a complex regulatory mechanism that determines the onset of antibiotic production (Bibb 2005; Liu et al. 2013; Martin and Liras 2010; van Wezel and McDowall 2011). The aur1 cluster (Fig. 1, Table 1) includes five genes, sa37, sa35, aur1PR2, aur1PR3, aur1PR4, encoding homologues of the family of Streptomyces antibiotic regulatory proteins (SARP) (Wietzorreck and Bibb 1997); seven genes, sa42, sa40, sa38, sa36, sagR, aur1R , aur1B , encoding homologues of the TetR family of transcriptional repressors (Ramos et al. 2005); and the sa28 gene encoding a homologue of the AraC family (Gallegos et al. 1997). This indicates that auricin biosynthesis undergoes complex regulation. Auricin-specific positive regulator Aur1P The first auricin-specific CSR gene characterized, aur1P, encodes a protein which belongs to the OmpR family of response regulators. They are characterized by an N-terminal CheY-like receiver domain and a winged-helix C-terminal domain responsible for DNA binding and interaction with RNA polymerase (Martinez-Hackert and Stock 1997). A similar conserved motif has also been identified in the lndEp promoter at the same position upstream of the putative −35 region of the promoters. Auricin-specific negative regulator Aur1R The other characterized auricin-specific CSR gene, aur1R (Fig. 1), encodes a protein of the TetR family (Ramos et al. 2005), which are mainly repressors. Like many TetR family regulators, Aur1R consists of an N-terminal helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain and a variable C-terminal effector- binding domain (Fig. 5a). Disruption of aur1R resulted in an increase of auricin production, thus confirming a negative role of Aur1R in regulating auricin production (Novakova et al. 2010a). Comparison of the amino acid sequence of Aur1R with protein sequence databases revealed the highest similar- ity to the subfamily of pseudo γ-butyrolactone (GBL) recep- tors (Fig. 5a), which constitute an independent branch in the phylogenetic tree of GBL receptors (Fig. 5b) and likely do not bind GBLs (Nishida et al. 2007). Microbial hormone-like GBLs, such as the well-known A-factor, play a key role in communication in actinomycetes, controlling development and/or antibiotic production. They bind to TetR family GBL receptors to derepress expression of further regulatory genes

mostly involved in the regulation of antibiotic production (Takano 2006). Like aur1R, the genes for the pseudo-GBL receptors are located in antibiotic clusters and the encoded regulators play a negative role in the antibiotic production by repression of CSR activator genes. Interestingly, several clus- ters containing pseudo-GBL receptor genes are cryptic or expressed under specific conditions (Xu et al. 2010). The following regulatory interactions represent the currently char- acterized pseudo-GBLs: ScbR2 directly represses the kasO gene, encoding a SARP family regulator of the cryptic type I PKS cluster cpk in S. coelicolor A3(2); similarly, JadR2 represses transcription of the jadomycin-specific jadR1 gene in S. venezuelae (Xu et al. 2010); AlpW negatively regulates the expression of the CSR alpV gene encoding a SARP family regulator in the kinamycin alp cluster of S. ambofaciens (Bunet et al. 2011); BarB participates in the repression of virginiamycin biosynthesis and controls vsmR expression in Streptomyces virginiae (Matsuno et al. 2004); TylQ negative- ly regulates tylosin biosynthesis through the repression of the CSR gene tylR in S. fradiae (Cundliffe 2008); SrrB is a negative regulator of both lankacidin and lankamycin in Streptomyces rochei (Arakawa et al. 2007); and PapR5 has been suggested to be involved in the negative regulation of pristinamycin biosynthesis in Streptomyces pristinaespiralis (Mast et al. 2011). Moreover, many pseudo-GBL receptor genes are under the direct control of GBL receptors that act early in the exponential phase, e.g., BarA-BarB (Matsuno et al. 2004), TylP-TylQ (Cundliffe 2008), AlpZ-AlpW (Bunet et al. 2011), and FarA-FarR2 (Kitani et al. 2008). The auricin cluster and its flanking regions contain five genes, sa37 , sa35 , aur1PR2, aur1PR3, aur1PR4 , which encode proteins with high similarity to SARPs, the most prominent family of CSRs (Fig. 1, Table 1). SARPs are specific to actinomycetes, and many of them are essential for the positive regulation of secondary metabolism, like ActII-ORF4 for actinorhodin and RedD for undecylprodigiosin in S. coelicolor (Fernandez-Moreno et al. 1991; Takano et al. 1992), DnrI for daunorubicin in Streptomyces peucetius (Sheldon et al. 2002), and TylS for tylosin in S. fradiae (Cundliffe 2008). The family contains also the well-studied global pleiotropic regulatory protein AfsR (Tanaka et al. 2007). SARPs are characterized by an N-terminal OmpR-

type helix-turn-helix (HTH) DNA binding domain, containing two helical segments (α2 and α3) separated by an 11-residue loop (Wietzorreck and Bibb 1997). This region is also con- served in all five SARP homologues from the aur1 cluster (Fig. 6a). Disruption of aur1PR3 and aur1PR4 dramatically reduced auricin production (Novakova et al. 2011b; Rehakova et al. 2013), whereas disruption of aur1PR2, sa35, and sa37 did not affect production (Novakova et al. 2011b, 2013). Expression of aur1PR3 and aur1PR4 is directed from single promoters, aur1Pr3p and aur1Pr4p (Fig. 1), which are dif- ferentially controlled. The aur1PR3p promoter is under direct negative control by the pseudo-GBL Aur1R, whereas aur1PR4p is directly positively regulated by the atypical response regulator Aur1P (Novakova et al. 2011b; Rehakova et al. 2013).

The SARP family regulators recognize direct repeats with- in the promoter regions of the genes they regulate. They are often heptameric direct repeats (5′-TCGAGXX-3′) with 4-bp or 15-bp spacers, located stringently 8 bp upstream of the −10 regions of promoters (Arias et al. 1999; Sheldon et al. 2002; Tanaka et al. 2007; Wietzorreck and Bibb 1997). Based on the phenotypes of both the aur1Pr3 and the aur1Pr4 mutant, Aur1Pr3 and Aur1PR4 should positively affect the expression of some auricin biosynthesis genes. Transcriptional studies revealed that the expression of 22 auricin biosynthetic genes, which are under the control of the aur1Ap promoter (Fig. 1), was dependent only on aur1PR3 . However, this effect is likely indirect, since no significant similarity to the correctly spaced direct repeats similar to SARP consensus sites has been found in the aur1Ap promoter or even in the aur1Pp promoter that directs expression of the gene encoding the auricin-specific CSR Aur1P (Novakova et al. 2011b; Rehakova et al. 2013). However, a single promoter, sa13p, located upstream of a putative operon of four genes sa13, sa12, sa11, sa10 (Fig. 1) encoding proposed auricin tailoring biosynthetic enzymes (Table 1) was shown to be dependent upon Aur1PR4 (Rehakova et al. 2013). Moreover, this pro- moter contains correctly located three heptameric sequences similar to the SARP consensus sequence (Rehakova et al. 2013; Fig. 6b). Therefore, it is likely that these genes may be direct targets of Aur1PR4. Sequence analysis of the aur1 cluster and the flanking regions revealed several other correct- ly spaced heptameric direct repeats in several promoters, and their functional role is currently in progress. The key question also stands whether these SARP regulators function coopera- tively or independently in the activation of the cognate pro- moters. Although the activation of antibiotic clusters is often activated by a single CSR gene, of which promoter is a site of regulation by a complex signal transduction pathway includ- ing many global regulators, as exemplified by the best-studied SARP, ActII-ORF4 (Liu et al. 2013; van Wezel and McDowall 2011), there are many examples, where several SARPs act together to activate antibiotic biosynthesis. For

instance, the tylosin cluster of S. fradiae contains two SARP family CRSs, TylS and TylT, and three additional regulators, TylR, TylU, and TylQ, are involved in regulation, though only TylS and TylR are essential for tylosin production. TylS together with the SARP helper protein TylU are responsible for the activation of tylR gene, which encodes a transcriptional activator for tylosin biosynthetic genes (Cundliffe 2008). Similarly, five CSRs, including even three SARPs, have been identified in the kinamycin alp cluster in S. ambofaciens However, only one, AlpV, appears to be involved in kinamycin regulation, and it acts as a transcriptional activator of the biosynthetic genes (Bunet et al. 2011). Two SARP family CRSs, SrrY and SrrZ, are responsible for the regulation of lankamycin production in S. rochei. Interestingly, the tran- scription of srrZ is directly controlled by SsrY (Suzuki et al. 2010). Similarly, two SARP family CSRs, NanR1 and NanR2, are required for the transcription of nanchangmycin genes, and they likely form a heterodimer to bind and activate the cognate genes (Yu et al. 2012). Therefore, SARP multiple homologues seem to vary in their regulatory mechanisms and interplay, which may be specific for the regulation of an individual antibiotic gene cluster. The key auricin-specific CSR of the atypical re- sponse regulator family Aur1P directs expression of the core auricin biosynthetic gene cluster (aur1A–aur1U), which are under the control of the aur1Ap promoter, induction of which coincides with the onset of stationary phase (12 h) (Fig. 3a). This blocking of the transcription of the auricin-specific CRSs is important until the cells are fully prepared for auricin production, by for example permitting expression of auricin resistance genes. Conclusions and further perspectives The results presented in this review suggest interesting and rather complex mechanisms, involving several transcriptional regulators, responsible for an intriguing auricin production pattern in a short time interval during growth of the production strain, S. aureofaciens CCM3239. A proposed feed-forward mechanism involving the negative regulator Aur1R seems to be responsible for the burst of production after entry into stationary phase, and a feedback mechanism by auricin inter- mediates interacting with the auricin-specific activator Aur1P shuts off further production. Moreover, synthesized auricin is rather labile during growth of the production strain, with pH as a critical parameter. Instability of auricin at higher pH suggests that the original habitat of the producing strain may be acid soil, where auricin would presumable be stable and maximally effective against competing microorganisms. The example of the complex regulatory scheme of auricin biosynthesis indi- cates that several checkpoints represented by auricin-specific CSRs control biosynthesis of this compound. Aur1P directs mainly the genes for biosynthesis of the aglycone and for resistance. Such auricin intermediates are likely not so toxic for the cells as the final glycosylated product.
